Capital constraints for small firms were so great that, at the end of the 1970s, it was considered probable that “the mass-production photovoltaic industry will consist entirely of wholly-owned subsidiaries of (large) conglomerates” [(
 
  75
 ), p. 28]. Paul Maycock, who ran the U.S. Department of Energy’s PV program, assumed in 1980 that the PV market would resemble the oligopolistic auto industry rather than the competitive electronics industry: “In the end,” he predicted, “we are going to have four companies, as in the automobile industry” (
 
  80
 ).
